604
01:00:02,760 --> 01:00:12,760
And we noticed that the people who are getting the mTOR, the rapholog, were reporting fewer respiratory tract infection as adverse events and they weren't flu.

605
01:00:12,760 --> 01:00:15,360
They were just all common respiratory tract infections.

606
01:00:15,860 --> 01:00:23,360
So it made us think, hey, if this is enhancing immune function, it's not going to be enhancing just the response to a flu vaccine.

607
01:00:23,360 --> 01:00:28,660
It's probably going to enhance the response to all sorts of different pathogens.

608
01:00:29,160 --> 01:00:39,460
So in our phase 2, we said, let's not only look at vaccine response, but let's actually look at infections that occur to see, are we decreasing infection rates?

609
01:00:40,260 --> 01:00:56,060
And in that phase 2, we also said, if mTOR inhibitors really do enhance immune function, this shouldn't be specific to a rapholog, which is a drug that changes the confirmation of mTOR and that's how it inhibits it.

610
01:00:56,760 --> 01:01:09,360
And we said, other kinds of mTOR inhibitors, which block the catalytic site, mTOR is an enzyme and they block the catalytic site, they should also have benefits if this is really an mTOR-mediated effect.

611
01:01:09,860 --> 01:01:17,360
So we looked at a rapholog and we looked at a catalytic inhibitor called RTB101 and we looked at the two together.

612
01:01:17,960 --> 01:01:23,460
And we looked not only at vaccine response, but we looked at infection rates for a whole year.

613
01:01:24,260 --> 01:01:31,560
Now RTB101 also has some PI3 kinase-inhabitory properties as well, doesn't it?

614
01:01:32,460 --> 01:01:39,360
So in a biochemical assay with, you know, an isolated enzyme, it inhibits PI3 kinase.

615
01:01:39,360 --> 01:01:45,460
And Novartis made this drug in the hopes that it would be a dual mTOR PI3 kinase inhibitor for cancer patients.

616
01:01:45,960 --> 01:01:52,860
But when you bring it in cells and in humans, you need much higher concentrations of RTB to inhibit PI3 kinase.

617
01:01:53,360 --> 01:01:59,260
And at the concentrations that are achievable in the clinic, it's mostly just a torque 1 inhibitor.

618
01:01:59,260 --> 01:02:04,360
It doesn't even get concentrations easily high enough to inhibit torque 2.

619
01:02:04,360 --> 01:02:12,260
So there's two mTOR complexes that contain mTOR and this is most potent inhibitor of the torque 1 complex.

620
01:02:12,760 --> 01:02:21,360
Now you achieved that in the first study by using the rapholog dosed intermittently at the lower doses.

621
01:02:21,360 --> 01:02:27,860
So I know the higher dose, which was 20 milligrams, you probably still get some C2 inhibition.

622
01:02:28,160 --> 01:02:32,460
But at the 0.5 daily, you probably don't get much.

623
01:02:32,660 --> 01:02:38,160
At the 5 weekly, you're probably mostly just hitting 1, correct, and not hitting 2.

624
01:02:38,160 --> 01:02:44,660
Exactly. Like we didn't see any real hyperglycemia or hyperlipidemia, which are the torque 2 side effects.

625
01:02:44,960 --> 01:02:54,960
So is it safe to say that at the doses you give RTB101, it has comparable mTORC1 inhibition to RAD001 at 5 milligrams weekly?

626
01:02:54,960 --> 01:02:56,460
Would that be the closest comparison?

627
01:02:56,660 --> 01:03:01,260
Probably more 0.5 milligram daily because we give RTB every day.

628
01:03:01,360 --> 01:03:02,360
Got it. Okay.

629
01:03:02,860 --> 01:03:07,860
And the reason you give it daily is of course the selectivity, the catalytic selectivity.

630
01:03:08,160 --> 01:03:12,160
And also it has a shorter half-life. Its half-life is 4 to 6 hours.

631
01:03:12,160 --> 01:03:18,960
So if you dose it once a day, it's inhibiting torque 1 for a shorter period of time than a verilimus.

632
01:03:18,960 --> 01:03:22,860
And if you give it twice a day, it's a little bit more persistent inhibition.

633
01:03:23,260 --> 01:03:35,460
Now explain, were there two studies, one that was combining these two, RAD001 plus RTB101, and then there was, was the protector study just RTB101 by itself?

634
01:03:35,960 --> 01:03:36,660
Correct.

635
01:03:37,160 --> 01:03:42,960
So we had two phase two studies looking at RTB alone and in combination with a verilimus.

636
01:03:43,060 --> 01:03:47,860
In the first study, the combination looked the best when you dose it for just 6 weeks.

637
01:03:48,360 --> 01:03:55,360
In the second study, when we extended dosing for 16 weeks in a sicker population, the RTB alone was better.

638
01:03:56,060 --> 01:04:00,660
So in both studies, RTB alone decreased respiratory tract infections.

639
01:04:01,360 --> 01:04:04,560
And in one, the combination did and the other, it didn't.

640
01:04:05,460 --> 01:04:12,460
So the study that did not meet its hard outcome was RTB101 alone, but not for vaccine response.

641
01:04:12,460 --> 01:04:16,060
Was it for, it was for total respiratory tract infections?

642
01:04:16,860 --> 01:04:21,360
No, and that's part of the problem for our phase three study.

643
01:04:21,360 --> 01:04:28,160
The FDA said we don't want an end point of laboratory confirmed respiratory tract infections where we had seen the benefit.

644
01:04:29,060 --> 01:04:30,560
And they said people don't care.

645
01:04:30,560 --> 01:04:32,160
This was pre-COVID-19.

646
01:04:32,160 --> 01:04:39,560
If a respiratory tract infection is laboratory confirmed, all they care about is how they feel and function and that's their symptoms.

647
01:04:39,860 --> 01:04:50,060
So what you have to do in the phase three is show you can decrease respiratory symptoms that are consistent with a respiratory tract infection, but don't have to be due to a respiratory tract infection.

648
01:04:50,060 --> 01:04:55,060
And we couldn't decrease the total respiratory symptoms that the elderly have.

649
01:04:55,560 --> 01:05:00,060
What it does look like we did was decrease the severity of the symptoms.

650
01:05:00,060 --> 01:05:02,560
But you weren't powered to detect that or were you?

651
01:05:02,560 --> 01:05:07,560
If you're looking at the laboratory confirmed infections, we were underpowered because there weren't very many.

652
01:05:08,060 --> 01:05:14,560
I think what the mTOR inhibitors are doing is not stopping people from getting infected.

653
01:05:14,560 --> 01:05:20,060
But if you get infected, there's a better immune response and your symptoms will be milder.

654
01:05:20,060 --> 01:05:26,560
Yeah, I mean, Nira, I've heard you say that because I want to come back and really talk about tame in some detail.

655
01:05:26,560 --> 01:05:36,560
But you know, it's a bit of a blessing in disguise that you didn't start tame a year ago because obviously it would have been interrupted as a result of this.

656
01:05:36,560 --> 01:05:40,560
I mean, all the clinical trials that I've been following closely have been interrupted by this.

657
01:05:40,560 --> 01:05:49,060
I follow very closely, for example, the clinical trials looking at liquid biopsies in cancer and all of a sudden these these trials are completely interrupted.

658
01:05:49,060 --> 01:05:51,060
So there's that there's that component to it.

659
01:05:51,060 --> 01:06:01,060
Of course, the flip side of that is depending on how large the study is, you might have actually inadvertently got another look at an indication you weren't necessarily thinking about.

660
01:06:01,060 --> 01:06:21,560
And I guess my question for you, Joan, is do you have enough subjects from the protector where there might be some lingering benefits or do you think that that window has closed and there's no benefit to going back and looking at the patients who received active drug in protector to see if they had any downstream benefits in terms of protection from SARS-CoV-2?

661
01:06:21,560 --> 01:06:23,560
