685
01:08:18,560 --> 01:08:22,560
It's their age, right? It's the biology of aging that is different.

686
01:08:22,560 --> 01:08:26,560
By the way, you previously said multi-morbidity.

687
01:08:26,560 --> 01:08:30,560
For me, multi-morbidity is how old you are biologically. That's all it is.

688
01:08:30,560 --> 01:08:36,560
Okay. 65% of the people have more than two diseases and 65% have more.

689
01:08:36,560 --> 01:08:39,060
Chronological and biological age are different.

690
01:08:39,060 --> 01:08:48,560
So I really think that part of what we have to discuss is the fact that we are defending the older individual.

691
01:08:48,560 --> 01:08:53,060
Whether there's something specific that can help is really great.

692
01:08:53,060 --> 01:09:02,060
But this goes not only to the immunity. It doesn't go to the inflammation, but goes also to how do we develop vaccines now?

693
01:09:02,060 --> 01:09:09,560
Because the vaccines that I'm seeing developing are not considering the older host in several ways.

694
01:09:09,560 --> 01:09:14,560
The New York Times today says that they even are going to test it over the age of 65.

695
01:09:14,560 --> 01:09:20,060
Okay. I think the vaccine is going to be such a trap.

696
01:09:20,060 --> 01:09:28,060
And the way to go over that is either realizing how to do it with the biology of aging and there's a way I'm ready to discuss with you some mechanisms.

697
01:09:28,060 --> 01:09:34,060
Or the elderly have to be on metformin or Apolog in order to get their immunity going.

698
01:09:34,060 --> 01:09:40,560
I think this is the next disaster. If we have a vaccine that doesn't protect the elderly, we did nothing.

699
01:09:40,560 --> 01:09:44,060
Let's talk a little bit about it. This is a topic that's near and dear to my heart.

700
01:09:44,060 --> 01:09:50,060
I'm getting involved in a study that's looking at a question from a slightly different angle, which is what's the durability of immune response?

701
01:09:50,060 --> 01:09:57,060
Historically, as you guys probably know, coronaviruses are not exactly the most robust at inducing durable immunity.

702
01:09:57,060 --> 01:10:01,060
In fact, if you remain immune for a year, that's considered reasonable.

703
01:10:01,060 --> 01:10:14,060
This poses a huge problem, which is what if after all the trouble of getting SARS-CoV-2, getting sick with COVID-19 bouncing back, you only have a year of immunity?

704
01:10:14,060 --> 01:10:24,060
The probability then that a vaccine is going to provide lifelong immunity, the way we get it from several of our most famous vaccines, seems quite low.

705
01:10:24,060 --> 01:10:29,060
Now you're in a situation of saying, well, gosh, what is the efficacy of a vaccine going to look like?

706
01:10:29,060 --> 01:10:34,060
Is this going to look like a 30% efficacious vaccine that you're going to need every year?

707
01:10:34,060 --> 01:10:39,060
Is it going to need to be supplemented by monoclonal antibodies in the most high-risk populations?

708
01:10:39,060 --> 01:10:44,060
I think we're all basically saying the same thing, which is there's a real risk here.

709
01:10:44,060 --> 01:10:48,060
So taken in order, what is the probability this virus is going away?

710
01:10:48,060 --> 01:10:51,060
Zero. I mean, it's somewhere between zero and epsilon.

711
01:10:51,060 --> 01:11:01,060
But the likelihood that SARS-CoV-2 magically mutates its way out of impacting humans is so low, it would be foolish to entertain that.

712
01:11:01,060 --> 01:11:08,060
So we now have a fifth coronavirus that's here to stay, except unlike its other four cousins, this one can really whack you.

713
01:11:08,060 --> 01:11:13,060
And then let's assume we can make some safe and efficacious vaccines.

714
01:11:13,060 --> 01:11:18,060
Are they really likely to keep you protected for five years, 10 years or more?

715
01:11:18,060 --> 01:11:23,060
Even without the genetic drift, based on what we know of other coronaviruses, that seems unlikely.

716
01:11:23,060 --> 01:11:27,060
Again, we're going to do a study to try to answer that question.

717
01:11:27,060 --> 01:11:37,060
But I think we do have to get ready for something that says, oh, man, we could be in a really unpleasant place where we never really naturally acquire herd immunity.

718
01:11:37,060 --> 01:11:44,060
And if that's true, not to fear monger, it means we need a better strategy around immune enhancement.

719
01:11:44,060 --> 01:11:47,060
And that's sort of my general take on this.

720
01:11:47,060 --> 01:11:50,060
Would you guys tone that down or ramp it up?

721
01:11:50,060 --> 01:11:54,060
I think it's quite a reasonable stance.

722
01:11:54,060 --> 01:12:02,060
And I think finding things that help generate persistent immunity is going to be important.

723
01:12:02,060 --> 01:12:04,060
Especially for the vulnerable population.

724
01:12:04,060 --> 01:12:13,060
I mean, that's the part that I think is really frustrating, is you were all struggling to come to grips with, well, what is the implication of this for school kids,

725
01:12:13,060 --> 01:12:18,060
where the restrictions seem so impossible to manage that it seems ridiculous, right?

726
01:12:18,060 --> 01:12:26,060
Like a seventh grader shouldn't have to be completely quarantined in the manner that we would think about quarantining a 70-year-old.

727
01:12:26,060 --> 01:12:33,060
So we have to be able to now think about immune-targeted therapies for the most immune vulnerable.

728
01:12:33,060 --> 01:12:36,060
I mean, I guess, Joan, how do you now think about juggling these things?

729
01:12:36,060 --> 01:12:43,060
Because I know that prior to COVID, you guys were already looking at an indication in Parkinson's disease, right?

730
01:12:43,060 --> 01:12:46,060
Help me understand from a preclinical standpoint what that was about.

731
01:12:46,060 --> 01:12:56,060
But then also, how do you now think about juggling resources, including time and just cognitive bandwidth around Parkinson's,

732
01:12:56,060 --> 01:13:03,060
which was sort of the path you were on, with now something that seems even more pressing and maybe even closer.

733
01:13:03,060 --> 01:13:07,060
I don't know if you think this is closer just based on the data.

734
01:13:07,060 --> 01:13:17,060
We have just reams of data now of using mTOR inhibitors to enhance immune function and older people's safety data

735
01:13:17,060 --> 01:13:24,060
and data on incidence, severity of respiratory tract infections, and a lot of biomarker data to start understanding

736
01:13:24,060 --> 01:13:27,060
what is actually going on in the immune system.

737
01:13:27,060 --> 01:13:29,060
So we're farthest ahead there.

738
01:13:30,060 --> 01:13:36,060
When we used to go and try to raise money for doing this kind of research, investors would just,

739
01:13:36,060 --> 01:13:40,060
we'd mentioned respiratory tract infections, and they would start to yawn.

740
01:13:40,060 --> 01:13:48,060
Nobody cared. They cared about cancer, and they cared about rare diseases, but they thought respiratory tract infections were boring.

741
01:13:48,060 --> 01:13:57,060
The nice thing about COVID-19 is it's making it obvious why enhancing immune function is a really important area

742
01:13:58,060 --> 01:14:02,060
and giving us a little bit more bandwidth to see if we can get it right.

743
01:14:02,060 --> 01:14:11,060
For the Parkinson's disease, it turns out neurodegenerative diseases, there's an accumulation of toxic protein aggregates.

744
01:14:11,060 --> 01:14:17,060
And if you enhance autophagy in preclinical models, that has benefit.

745
01:14:17,060 --> 01:14:21,060
I mentioned, raphologs aren't great at inducing autophagy.

746
01:14:21,060 --> 01:14:27,060
RTB at high doses is very good, but it's hard to achieve those concentrations in the brain.

747
01:14:27,060 --> 01:14:35,060
If you use the two of those together, you can lower the concentration of RTB that's needed to induce autophagy,

748
01:14:35,060 --> 01:14:38,060
so you don't have to get so much across the blood-brain barrier.

749
01:14:38,060 --> 01:14:44,060
And that was the reason we did the trial of that combination in Parkinson's disease.

750
01:14:44,060 --> 01:14:49,060
Now, Matt Kaberlin wrote a really elegant piece, gosh, it's probably been a year ago now, where he said,

